    {"instruction": "Why does Beanstalk Control play Up the Beanstalk?", "input": "", "output": "Up the Beanstalk is a 2-mana enchantment that draws a card whenever you cast a spell with mana value 5 or greater. In Legacy, Force of Will (MV 5), Solitude (MV 5), Fury (MV 5), and Subtlety (MV 5) all trigger it even when cast for their free alternative costs. This turns pitch spells into cantrips, generating absurd card advantage while doing things you already wanted to do."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Beanstalk Control play Solitude?", "input": "", "output": "Solitude is a free removal spell that exiles a creature by pitching a white card. In Beanstalk, it also triggers Up the Beanstalk to draw a card, making the pitch cost less painful. The 3/2 lifelink body is relevant when evoked and blinked with Ephemerate, gaining 3 life and exiling another creature. It handles problematic threats like Murktide Regent and True-Name Nemesis that dodge other removal."},
    # Reanimator
    {"instruction": "Why does Reanimator play Reanimate over other reanimation spells?", "input": "", "output": "Reanimate costs just 1 black mana, making it the cheapest and fastest reanimation spell. The life cost equal to the target creature's mana value is steep (8 for Griselbrand, 7 for Archon of Cruelty) but irrelevant when the reanimated creature immediately takes over the game. At 1 mana, Reanimate can be cast through Daze and Thalia while still leaving mana for protection."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Reanimator play Archon of Cruelty?", "input": "", "output": "Archon of Cruelty has an ETB that forces the opponent to sacrifice a creature or planeswalker, discard a card, and lose 3 life, while you draw a card and gain 3 life. This 6-for-1 swing on entry is devastating even if Archon is immediately removed. Unlike Griselbrand, Archon cannot be exiled by Karakas (it is not legendary) and provides value regardless of your life total."},
    {"instruction": "Why did Reanimator decline after the Entomb ban?", "input": "", "output": "Entomb was a 1-mana instant that put any creature directly into the graveyard, enabling turn-1 Entomb into turn-1 Reanimate kills. Without it, Reanimator must use slower discard outlets like Faithful Mending or Careful Study, which cost 2 mana and require drawing the creature first. This extra turn of setup gives opponents time to find Surgical Extraction, Force of Will, or graveyard hate."},
