    {"instruction": "Why does Dredge play Lion's Eye Diamond?", "input": "", "output": "LED is the best card in Dredge because discarding your hand is an UPSIDE - it puts dredge cards into the graveyard where you want them. Cracking LED in response to a draw effect lets you dredge on the next draw while also generating 3 mana for Faithless Looting flashback or other spells. Turn-1 LED into draw spell is the explosive start that makes Dredge competitive."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Dredge play Ichorid?", "input": "", "output": "Ichorid returns from the graveyard to the battlefield for free at the beginning of your upkeep by exiling a black creature card. Since Dredge fills the graveyard with creatures naturally, Ichorid provides a recurring threat that costs zero mana and zero cards from hand. Multiple Ichorids coming back every turn create inevitability even through removal."},
    # Red Stompy
    {"instruction": "Why does Red Stompy play Blood Moon?", "input": "", "output": "Blood Moon turns all nonbasic lands into Mountains, shutting off dual lands, fetchlands, Wasteland, Urza's Saga, Dark Depths, and utility lands. In a format where most decks run 15+ nonbasics, Blood Moon effectively locks opponents out of casting their spells. Red Stompy only needs Mountains, so Blood Moon does not affect its own mana base at all."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Red Stompy play The One Ring?", "input": "", "output": "The One Ring provides protection from everything for a turn (buying time to set up locks) and draws increasing numbers of cards each turn. In a prison deck that aims to stop the opponent from playing, The One Ring provides the card advantage needed to find more lock pieces and threats. The cumulative life loss is acceptable because the opponent should be locked out by then."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Red Stompy play Chrome Mox?", "input": "", "output": "Chrome Mox provides turn-1 acceleration by imprinting a nonartifact, nonland card. Combined with Ancient Tomb or City of Traitors, Chrome Mox enables turn-1 Blood Moon, turn-1 Chalice of the Void on 1, or turn-1 Trinisphere. The card disadvantage of imprinting is acceptable because a resolved turn-1 lock piece often wins the game by itself."},
