    {"instruction": "Why is Storm favored against Death and Taxes?", "input": "", "output": "D&T has no free counterspells to stop the combo turn. Thalia taxes Storm's spells by 1 each, but Storm can remove Thalia with a bounce spell or simply generate enough mana to pay through the tax. D&T's clock is too slow to kill before Storm goes off on turns 3-4, and Rishadan Port tapping one land is insufficient disruption against a deck that generates 10+ mana in a single turn."},
    {"instruction": "Why is Doomsday harder to play than other combo decks?", "input": "", "output": "Doomsday requires you to construct a 5-card pile that wins through whatever disruption the opponent might have, accounting for cards in hand, mana available, and cards you need to draw through. Different matchups require different piles (play around Surgical, play around Force of Will, play around Stifle). A wrong pile construction means you lose with no recourse. Other combo decks just need to find pieces and cast them."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Merfolk struggle in the current metagame?", "input": "", "output": "Orcish Bowmasters in 29% of decks is devastating against a deck full of 2-toughness creatures. Bowmasters kills Lord of Atlantis on sight and punishes every cantrip Merfolk casts. The deck also lacks free countermagic beyond Force of Will, making it weaker against combo than Delver variants. True-Name Nemesis is the one bright spot but costs 3 mana in a deck that wants to curve out with lords."},
    {"instruction": "Why is Ocelot Pride Midrange strong against creature decks?", "input": "", "output": "Ocelot Pride creates tokens on every non-combat damage trigger, so Lightning Bolt, Bowmasters pings, and Guide of Souls drain all generate extra bodies. The deck goes wide faster than most creature strategies can manage, and Swords to Plowshares plus Solitude handle any individual large threat. Against decks like D&T or Elves, Ocelot simply out-values them in creature combat."},
    {"instruction": "Why does Infect have polarized matchups?", "input": "", "output": "Infect wins by dealing just 10 poison with pump spells on an unblocked infect creature, which can happen as early as turn 2. Against decks without removal (combo, some prison), this is virtually unbeatable speed. But against decks with efficient removal (Swords to Plowshares, Lightning Bolt, Orcish Bowmasters), killing the infect creature in response to a pump spell is a devastating blowout that wastes multiple cards."},

    # === MORE MANA BASE AND CONSTRUCTION ===
    {"instruction": "How do you build a mana base for a three-color Legacy deck?", "input": "", "output": "Start with 4 fetchlands that find both your primary and secondary duals (e.g., Polluted Delta in UBx). Run 3-4 of your primary dual land, 1-2 of your secondary dual, and 2-3 basics (at least one of each primary color). Add 4 Wasteland if your deck is tempo-oriented. Total lands typically 18-20 for tempo, 22-24 for midrange. The key is ensuring 14+ sources of your primary color for turn-1 plays and 10+ of each secondary color."},
    {"instruction": "When should a Legacy deck play Ancient Tomb?", "input": "", "output": "Ancient Tomb belongs in decks that benefit from 2 colorless mana on turn 1 and can tolerate the 2 life per tap. This means prison decks (Chalice, Trinisphere, Blood Moon), artifact combo (Mystic Forge, Painter), Eldrazi (creatures cost 2+), and Show and Tell variants. It does NOT belong in tempo decks that need colored mana for cantrips or control decks that need every life point. The 2 life per use adds up fast."},
    {"instruction": "Why do some decks play City of Traitors over Ancient Tomb?", "input": "", "output": "City of Traitors provides 2 colorless mana without the 2 life cost, which matters in Eldrazi and prison decks that activate it many times. The downside is that it is sacrificed when you play another land, so it is better in decks that want to deploy one big play early (turn-1 Chalice + creature) rather than sustained mana production. Many decks play a split of both to maximize explosive starts."},
    {"instruction": "How many lands should a combo deck play?", "input": "", "output": "Combo decks typically play 14-18 lands depending on their mana curve and acceleration. Storm plays 14-15 with rituals providing the rest. Sneak and Show plays 16-18 with Lotus Petal and Ancient Tomb. Oops plays 0 (by design). Doomsday plays 16-17 with Dark Ritual. The key is having enough mana to cast your combo pieces on turns 2-3 while maximizing spell density for consistency."},
    {"instruction": "What is the correct fetchland configuration for Dimir Tempo?", "input": "", "output": "Most Dimir Tempo lists play 8 fetchlands: 4 Polluted Delta (finds Underground Sea and both basics) plus 4 Misty Rainforest, Flooded Strand, or Scalding Tarn (any blue fetch that finds Island). The second set of fetches is chosen based on splash potential: Misty for green sideboard cards, Scalding Tarn for Volcanic Island splash, Flooded Strand for Tundra splash. All 8 find basic Island, which is the most important basic."},

    # === MORE SIDEBOARD STRATEGY ===
    {"instruction": "How should I sideboard against Eldrazi?", "input": "", "output": "Chalice of the Void on 1 is their key card, so bring in cards that cost 0 or 2+ mana. Force of Vigor destroys Chalice for free. Engineered Explosives on 0 catches Chalice. Keep your big threats (Murktide survives anything Eldrazi throws at it). Cut low-impact 1-mana spells that get countered by Chalice. The matchup is about resolving threats through Chalice and going bigger than their creatures."},
    {"instruction": "How should I sideboard against Lands?", "input": "", "output": "Blood Moon effects are the best answer to Lands since their entire strategy is built on nonbasic lands. Surgical Extraction on Life from the Loam shuts down their recursion engine. Dress Down prevents Thespian's Stage from copying Dark Depths. Price of Progress deals massive damage against a deck with 30+ nonbasic lands. Cut your Dazes (they have few spells to counter) and creature removal (they have few creatures)."},
    {"instruction": "How should I sideboard against Ocelot Pride?", "input": "", "output": "Bring in sweepers like Toxic Deluge (kills through Solitude protection) and Massacre (free against white). Engineered Explosives on 1 catches most of their threats. Keep Orcish Bowmasters (excellent against their token generation). Cut Daze (they have enough mana to pay) and narrow countermagic. The goal is to go bigger with card advantage and sweepers rather than trying to one-for-one their value engine."},
    {"instruction": "How should I sideboard against Doomsday?", "input": "", "output": "Keep all countermagic (Force, Daze, Flusterstorm). Bring in Surgical Extraction (exile Doomsday from graveyard after they cast it, or target Thassa's Oracle). Stifle the Oracle ETB trigger if you play it. Thoughtseize is excellent since stripping Doomsday itself prevents the combo. The key is preventing Doomsday from resolving or disrupting the pile execution afterward."},
    {"instruction": "When should I bring in Mindbreak Trap?", "input": "", "output": "Mindbreak Trap is best against Storm and Oops All Spells because it exiles spells for free when the opponent has cast 3+ spells this turn (which both decks do every combo turn). It cannot be countered by Flusterstorm since it is exiled rather than countered. Bring it in against any deck that chains multiple spells in a single turn. It is dead against fair decks that cast one spell per turn."},
    {"instruction": "When should I bring in Null Rod or Collector Ouphe?", "input": "", "output": "Null Rod and Collector Ouphe shut off all activated abilities of artifacts. Bring them in against Painter (stops Grindstone activation), 8-Cast and Affinity (stops Urza's Saga, artifact mana), Mystic Forge (stops the Forge itself), and any deck heavily reliant on artifact mana (Lion's Eye Diamond, Lotus Petal, Chrome Mox). Be careful not to board them in when your own deck uses artifact mana."},
    {"instruction": "How do I use Force of Vigor effectively?", "input": "", "output": "Force of Vigor destroys two artifacts and/or enchantments for free by pitching a green card. It is devastating against Chalice of the Void (on 1 and 2), Urza's Saga and its Construct tokens, Blood Moon, Ensnaring Bridge, and The One Ring. The two-for-one aspect makes it better than Nature's Claim in matchups where the opponent has multiple problematic artifacts or enchantments. Always pitch it rather than hard-casting if possible."},

