    {"instruction": "What is the 60-card rule in Legacy deck construction?", "input": "", "output": "Legacy decks must have a minimum of 60 cards in the main deck and up to 15 in the sideboard. While you can play more than 60, virtually every competitive deck plays exactly 60 because more cards reduces consistency - you are less likely to draw your best cards. The only exception is Yorion companion decks that play 80 cards, accepting reduced consistency for the companion advantage."},
    {"instruction": "How do I choose between a 60-card and 80-card build?", "input": "", "output": "Play 80 cards only with Yorion, Sky Nomad as companion, and only if your deck has enough blink targets to justify Yorion's ETB. Death and Taxes (Yorion BW), Beanstalk Control (Yorion builds), and some Bant builds use 80 cards. The 20 extra cards reduce consistency but Yorion's guaranteed value compensates. If your deck does not have strong ETB creatures to blink, 60 cards is strictly better."},
    {"instruction": "How do I decide which cards to play 4 copies of?", "input": "", "output": "Play 4 copies of cards you want to see in every opening hand and every game. In Dimir Tempo, that means 4 Brainstorm, 4 Ponder, 4 Force of Will, 4 Daze, 4 Wasteland, 4 Bowmasters. Play 3 copies of cards that are great but occasionally redundant (3 Murktide, 3 Thoughtseize). Play 1-2 copies of situational cards or legends (1 Karakas, 2 Snuff Out). The cantrips help find your 1-2 ofs when needed."},
    {"instruction": "What does a well-constructed Legacy deck curve look like?", "input": "", "output": "Tempo decks peak at 1-2 mana: 20+ spells at 0-1 mana, 8-12 at 2 mana, 2-4 at 3+ mana. Control decks are flatter: 10-12 at 1 mana, 8-10 at 2, 4-6 at 3, 2-4 at 4+. Combo decks are bimodal: many 0-1 mana spells (rituals, cantrips) and a few high-impact 3-4 mana payoffs. Prison decks spike at 0 and 3: fast mana (0) into lock pieces (3). Legacy is defined by mana efficiency - 4+ mana spells need to be game-winning to justify their slot."},

    # === ARCHETYPE SELECTION GUIDANCE ===
    {"instruction": "I like controlling the board and winning with inevitability. What Legacy deck should I play?", "input": "", "output": "Beanstalk Control or Jeskai Control are your best options. Beanstalk generates card advantage through Up the Beanstalk triggers on pitch spells, plays sweepers and removal, and wins through accumulated value. Jeskai Control uses Swords to Plowshares, Lightning Bolt, countermagic, and planeswalkers to grind opponents out. Lands is another option if you want a non-traditional control deck that operates entirely through lands."},
    {"instruction": "I like fast, aggressive decks that win before the opponent sets up. What Legacy deck should I play?", "input": "", "output": "For combo speed: Oops All Spells can win turn 1, Storm and Doomsday win turns 2-3, Sneak and Show wins turns 2-3. For aggressive creature speed: Ocelot Pride Midrange deploys efficient threats from turn 1 and overwhelms quickly, Burn goes face from turn 1. For tempo aggression: Dimir Tempo and Izzet Delver deploy cheap threats and protect them with free countermagic while denying opponent's mana."},
    {"instruction": "I want to play a deck that taxes and disrupts the opponent. What Legacy deck should I play?", "input": "", "output": "Death and Taxes is the premier tax deck: Thalia taxes spells, Rishadan Port and Wasteland tax mana, and Aether Vial lets you deploy creatures while keeping tax mana open. Red Stompy provides artifact-based prison with Chalice of the Void, Blood Moon, and Trinisphere. Eldrazi combines Chalice prison with large aggressive creatures. All three specialize in preventing the opponent from playing their game."},
    {"instruction": "I have a small budget. What competitive Legacy deck can I build?", "input": "", "output": "Oops All Spells at $1100 is the cheapest tier 1 deck - zero dual lands needed. Burn at $1500 is a consistent performer with no expensive Reserved List cards. Belcher at $1200 is similar to Oops in strategy and price. Red Stompy at $2500 avoids dual lands and uses Ancient Tomb as its main investment. Eldrazi at $2100 is all colorless. All five can win tournaments and serve as entry points into Legacy."},
    {"instruction": "I want to play a unique brew in Legacy. How do I approach it?", "input": "", "output": "Start by identifying a meta weakness: if 14.6% of the field is Dimir Tempo, build something that beats UB. Study underplayed archetypes with high win rates (Aluren won the Showcase Qualifier at only 1.2% meta share). Use established Legacy shells as foundations (cantrip + Force of Will, Ancient Tomb + Chalice, Green Sun's Zenith toolbox) and add your unique angle. Test extensively against tier 1 decks before committing - a brew that loses to the top 3 decks is just a bad deck."},

